<b><center>Propositional Logic </center></b><font size="--">


<br>
<FONT FACE="Arial"><P> For students taking MatM153, the lecture notes referred to in this Learning Plan are those entitled &quot;Boolean Algebra&quot;.</P>

<br>
<P>For the purpose of general communication we often express ourselves using questions, exclamations and so forth, but to communicate facts or information of some sort we use statements.</P>

<br>
<B><P>Definition</P>
</B>
<P>A <B>proposition</B> is a statement which, as given, is either true or false.</P>

<P>True and false are truth values.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Examples</P>
</B>
<P>6 is an even number.   This is a proposition because it is true.</P>

<P>6 is an odd number.   This is a proposition because it is false.</P>

<P>What age are you ?   This is not a proposition.</P>

<P>He is intelligent.   This is a proposition because it can be true or false</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Notation</P>
</B>
<P>We normally use p, q, r, s, t, …. to denote propositions.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Compound Propositions</P>
</B>
<P>To vary our conversations we do not confine ourselves to simple statements (propositions).   We combine simple propositions with connecting words to make compound propositions.   The truth value of a compound proposition depends on the truth value of its components and the connecting words used.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<B><P>Conjunction</P>
</B>
<P>Let p and q be any two propositions.   The compound proposition &quot;<B>p and q</B>&quot; is called the <B>conjunction</B> of p and q.   It is denoted symbolically as <B>p<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
q</B> .</P>

<P>We can say that if p is true and q is true then p<FONT FACE="Symbol">&#217;</FONT>
q is also true. </P>

<B><P>Example </P>
</B>
<P>Consider the two true propositions,</P>

<P>I am a student at G.C.U.</P>
<P>My programme is BSc Computing.</P>

<P>Then we would consider the resulting proposition :</P>

<P>I am a student at G.C.U. and my programme is BSc Computing to be true.</P>

<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>&nbsp;</P>
<P>We can summarise the effects of conjunction by a <B>truth table</B>.</P>
